antage point of religious studies, and what does attention to the law offer back to scholars of religion? Religion, Law, USA considers all these questions and more. Each chapter considers a specific keyword in the study of religion and law, such as “conscience,” “establishment,” “secularity,” and “personhood.” Contributors consider specific case studies related to each term, and then expand their analyses to discuss broader implications for the practice and study of American religion. Incorporating pieces from leading voices in the field, this book is an indispensable addition to the scholarship on religion and law in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aFreedom of religionzUnited States. 0aReligion and lawzUnited States. 0aReligion and statezUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aAI.  aBlackpentecostalism.  aBoy Scouts of America v Dale.  aBoy Scouts of America.  aBrown v Board.  aBurwell v Hobby Lobby.  aCatholicism.  aConstitution.  aDred Scott v Sandford.  aElk Grove Unified School District.  aEmployment Division v Smith.  aEverson v Board of Education.  aFirst Amendment.  aGloucester County School Board v GG.  aHobby Lobby.  aLawrence v Texas.  aLittle Sisters of the Poor.  aMuslim ban.  aNative Americans.  aNomos and Narrative.  aPage Law.  aPledge of Allegiance.  aProtestantism.  aRoe v Wade.  aSupreme Court.  aTaíno.  aTrump v Hawaii.  aUS legal history.  aUS v Seeger.  aUnited States.  aabortion.  aamicus curiae.  aartificial intelligence.  aartificial persons.  aautonomous cars.  acivil rights.  acolonialism.  acomparison.  aconscientious objection.  acritical race theory.  adoctrine of discovery.  aethics.  afree exercise.  agay rights.  aheterosexuality.  ahomosexuality.  ale